data.enText: a very small living thing that can cause infection and disease
Dirty hands can be a breeding ground for germs.
an early stage of the development of sth

data.chText: 一个绝妙的主意就是从这里萌发的。
data.enText: Here was the germ of a brilliant idea.
the part of a plant or an animal that can develop into a new one

tr: a minute life form (especially a disease-causing bacterium)
the term is not in technical use
a small apparently simple structure (as a fertilized egg) from which new tissue can develop into a complete organism
anything that provides inspiration for later work

value.def: A germ is a very small organism that causes disease.

example.ex: Chlorine is widely used to kill germs.
...a germ that destroyed hundreds of millions of lives.
example.tran: 夺去了无数生命的细菌

value.def: The germ of something such as an idea is something which developed or might develop into that thing.

example.ex: The germ of an idea took root in Rosemary's mind...
example.tran: 罗斯玛丽心里萌生了一个念头。

example.ex: This was the germ of a book.

partsOfSpeech.d: 细菌（如种子般滋生繁衍）

partsOfSpeech.dec: germ 种子 + ane …的 → 来自同一品种 → 关系密切的
germin〔= germ〕种子 + ate 做，造成，使… → 种子萌动 → 发芽
